    "body": "## Problem\r\nOn Git versions 2.13..2.26 there is a bug that prevents using `stash --message`.\r\n\r\nhttps://git.kernel.org/pub/scm/git/git.git/commit/?id=8c3713cede71e4741dac546f787734627329f55b\r\n\r\n## Solution\r\nUse the full `stash push --message` form to avoid that bug.\r\n\r\nFix #38671",
    "closed_at": null,
    "comment_data": [],
    "comment_regular_data": [
        {
            "author_association": "MEMBER",
            "body": "Thanks for the PR!\r\n\r\n> Calling `git stash` without an explicit subcommand should be treated as `git stash push`, but older Git releases do not accept '-m' with that short form.\r\n\r\nThat's a bit confusing, since `git stash push` *does* accept the `--message`. The real problem seems to be that up to 2.16.6 [`git stash` was equivalent to `git stash save`](https://git-scm.com/docs/git-stash/2.14.6), but afterwards - [equivalent to `git stash push`](https://git-scm.com/docs/git-stash/2.16.6).\r\n\r\nI think the more appropriate fix here would be to use a more recent cutoff for the adding the message. This doesn't add any lines and it is okay to not have a minor quality of life improvement if the Git version is 5+ years old.\r\n\r\nBased on the above documentation links, the cutoff should be 2.16.6. But since #38671 reports 2.25.1, it doesn't look correct. @skewb1k, could you please find out the oldest possible cutoff version here?",
