        {
            "author_association": "CONTRIBUTOR",
            "body": "> I think the more appropriate fix here would be to use a more recent cutoff for the adding the message. This doesn't add any lines and it is okay to not have a minor quality of life improvement if the Git version is 5+ years old.\r\n\r\nMakes sense, so it is the version check should be fixed to call `stash --message` only if the version supports it properly. Though I think there is no harm in adding `push` for explicitness, if it is going to be only for >=2.13 anyway?\r\n\r\n> > Calling `git stash` without an explicit subcommand should be treated as `git stash push`, but older Git releases do not accept '-m' with that short form.\r\n> \r\n> That's a bit confusing, since `git stash push` _does_ accept the `--message`. The real problem seems to be that up to 2.16.6 [`git stash` was equivalent to `git stash save`](https://git-scm.com/docs/git-stash/2.14.6), but afterwards - [equivalent to `git stash push`](https://git-scm.com/docs/git-stash/2.16.6).\r\n> \r\n> Based on the above documentation links, the cutoff should be 2.16.6. But since #38671 reports 2.25.1, it doesn't look correct. @skewb1k, could you please find out the oldest possible cutoff version here?\r\n\r\nYeah, I too don't get why it is like that. According to the docs this should work, and I didn't find any mention in the release notes of a such bug. I'll try to bisect to the exact version.",
